literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this context: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(a) Following the slides, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\hat{b}_{1}=\frac{s_{xy}}{s_{x}^{2}}\qquad\qquad\hat{b}_{0}=\overline{y}-\hat{b}_{1}\overline{x}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{xy}$
\end_inset

 refers to the sample covariance, 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{x}^{2}$
\end_inset

 refers to the sample variance, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{y}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{x}$
\end_inset

 refer to sample means.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It's intuitive and easy to verify that 
\begin_inset Formula $E\left[s_{xy}\right]=\sigma_{xy}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $E\left(s_{x}^{2}\right)=\sigma^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Note: for these estimates to be consistent we have to divide by 
\begin_inset Formula $n-1$
\end_inset

 instead of 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "Bessel's correction"
target "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bessel%27s_correction"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Informally, this seems to suggest that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E\left[\hat{b}_{1}\right]\approx\frac{\sigma_{xy}}{\sigma^{2}},
\]

\end_inset

which would then imply 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E\left[\hat{b}_{0}\right]\approx\mu_{y}-\frac{\sigma_{xy}}{\sigma^{2}}\mu_{x}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

